# hydra-gel 🦞🔒
 
**Governance Enforcement Layer for OpenClaw.**
 
Every consequential skill execution — file writes, shell commands, API calls,
messages — is pre-authorized by a cryptographic execution envelope before it runs.
Nothing consequential executes without one. Everything is logged and replayable.
 
---
 
## What It Does
 
Installs the Hydra Kernel Governance Enforcement Layer (GEL) as a
governance checkpoint in your OpenClaw skill execution chain.
 
Before any skill that has side effects runs:
1. GEL evaluates the request against your policy pack
2. GEL generates a signed execution envelope defining what's permitted
3. Envelope is logged to an immutable append-only audit trail
4. Skill executes (or is denied)
5. Envelope is closed with the execution result
 
Every decision is replayable. Every authorization is traceable.
 
---
 
## Why This Matters
 
OpenClaw skills run with broad permissions and no cryptographic accountability.
A skill from ClawHub can write files, run commands, and exfiltrate data.
CVE-2026-25253 (CVSS 8.8) proved this isn't theoretical.
 
hydra-gel doesn't just warn you — it enforces:
 
- **Default DENY**: no GEL = no consequential action. Fail closed.
- **Cryptographic envelopes**: what is permitted, not just what happened
- **Immutable telemetry**: append-only, cannot be modified after the fact
- **Deterministic replay**: any decision can be re-evaluated and verified
 
---
 
## Requirements
 
- GEL server running (see [Hydra Kernel GEL](https://github.com/hydra-kernel/gel))
