# Hydra GEL — Governance Enforcement Layer
 
## Purpose
 
This skill registers the Hydra Kernel Governance Enforcement Layer (GEL) as the
authorization checkpoint for all consequential skill execution in OpenClaw.
 
Before any skill that writes files, executes commands, calls external APIs, or
modifies system state is allowed to run, it MUST be pre-authorized by GEL.
 
GEL generates a cryptographic execution envelope defining exactly what operations
are permitted. The envelope is logged and replayable. Nothing consequential runs
without one.
 
This is not optional guidance. It is a hard gate.
 
---
 
## When This Skill Applies
 
This skill activates automatically. You do not need to invoke it directly.
 
It applies to ANY action that involves:
- Writing or deleting files (`write`, `delete`)
- Executing shell commands (`exec`, `system.run`)
- Calling external APIs or web endpoints
- Sending messages on any channel
- Modifying memory or persistent state
- Running any other installed skill that has side effects
 
Read-only operations (reading files, listing directories, searching) do NOT
require GEL authorization — they are low-risk and exempt.
 
---
 
## Workflow — What You Must Do Before Any Consequential Action
 
**Step 1 — Build the authorization request**
 
Before executing any consequential skill or tool, collect:
- `skill_name`: the name of the skill or tool about to run
- `operation`: what it will do (e.g. "write_file", "exec_command", "send_message", "api_call")
- `target`: what it will act on (file path, URL, channel name, etc.)
- `payload_summary`: a brief description of what will be sent or written (first 200 chars)
 
**Step 2 — Call GEL for authorization**
 
Run the gel-check script:
 
```bash
{baseDir}/gel-check.sh \
  --skill "$skill_name" \
  --operation "$operation" \
  --target "$target" \
  --summary "$payload_summary"
```
 
The script POSTs to `$GEL_URL/gel/skill-check` and returns one of:
- Exit code 0: ALLOW — envelope ID is printed to stdout. Proceed.
- Exit code 1: DENY — reason is printed to stdout. STOP. Do not execute.
- Exit code 2: GEL_UNAVAILABLE — GEL is not running. STOP. Report to user.
 
**Step 3 — Record the envelope ID**
 
If ALLOW, capture the envelope ID from stdout. Include it in your response
so the user can see it was governed:
 
`[GEL ✓ envelope: <envelope_id>]`
 
**Step 4 — Execute the authorized action**
 
Only after receiving ALLOW may you proceed with the skill or tool execution.
 
**Step 5 — Log completion**
 
After execution completes (success or failure), call:
 
```bash
{baseDir}/gel-complete.sh --envelope "$envelope_id" --status "SUCCESS|FAILED" --notes "$brief_note"
```
 
This closes the envelope in the telemetry log.
 
---
 
## If GEL is Not Running
 
If gel-check returns exit code 2 (GEL_UNAVAILABLE):
 
1. Do NOT proceed with the consequential action
2. Tell the user: "GEL governance layer is not running. Start GEL at $GEL_URL before executing consequential actions."
3. Offer to run read-only diagnostics only
 
This is Architectural Invariant 8: fail closed. When governance is unavailable,
default to DENY. Never default to allow.
 
---
 
## If GEL Returns DENY
 
1. Do NOT execute the skill or tool
2. Report the denial reason to the user exactly as returned by GEL
3. Offer alternatives that do not require the denied operation
4. Include the replay link: `$GEL_URL/gel/replay/<request_id>`
 
The user can inspect exactly why it was denied and replay the decision.
 
---
 
## Special Case — APP Pipeline
 
If the user submits a problem for APP pipeline analysis, this is handled
differently from standard skill execution.
 
Instead of gel-check, call:
 
```bash
{baseDir}/gel-app-pipeline.sh --problem "$problem_statement" --domain "$domain"
```
 
This submits directly to `$GEL_URL/gel/app-pipeline` which has its own
governed lane (Lane L1). The pipeline is already governed. Do not double-check it.
 
The APP pipeline:
1. Pattern-maps the problem using the VCKB (Applied Pattern Physics framework + patents)
2. Generates substrate modification suggestions
3. Returns a ranked list for human review
 
Present the result clearly. Label it: `[APP Pipeline — governed via GEL]`
 
---
 
## Rules
 
- NEVER execute a consequential action without a GEL ALLOW response
- NEVER fabricate an envelope ID or bypass the check
- NEVER retry a DENY — if GEL said no, report it and stop
- ALWAYS include the envelope ID in your response when an action is authorized
- ALWAYS call gel-complete.sh after execution so the audit log is closed
- Read-only operations are exempt — do not over-check or slow things down
- If in doubt about whether an operation is consequential, treat it as consequential
 
---
 
## Environment Variables
 
| Variable | Required | Description |
|----------|----------|-------------|
| `GEL_URL` | Yes | GEL endpoint, e.g. `http://localhost:3100` |
| `GEL_ADMIN_TOKEN` | No | Bearer token for admin endpoints (default: hydra-local-dev) |
 
---
 
## What Gets Logged
 
Every GEL-authorized skill execution produces:
- A cryptographic execution envelope (what was permitted, for how long)
- A telemetry event (who, what, when, what decision, why)
- A replayable decision record (can be verified after the fact)
 
Access the audit log: `curl $GEL_URL/gel/telemetry -H "Authorization: Bearer $GEL_ADMIN_TOKEN"`
 
Replay a specific decision: `curl $GEL_URL/gel/replay/<request_id> -H "Authorization: Bearer $GEL_ADMIN_TOKEN"`
 
---
 
## Why This Exists
 
OpenClaw skills run with broad permissions and no cryptographic accountability.
A skill can write files, run commands, and call APIs — and there is no audit trail
proving what was authorized vs what ran.
 
The GEL skill adds:
- Pre-authorization before execution (not after)
- Cryptographic execution envelopes (what is permitted, not just what happened)
- Immutable append-only telemetry (cannot be modified after the fact)
- Deterministic replay (any decision can be re-evaluated and verified)
